title.narrative: By 2022, key institutions and service providers have increased capacity to boost the coverage and quality of specialised child protection services.

description.narrative: UNICEF in partnership with the Government, NGOs and CBOs made an effort to improve the quality of child protection services by setting standards/guidelines; to increase the coverage of child protection services by expanding partnerships and community-based mechanisms; and to design evidence-based demand-creation strategy to address the bottlenecks in help-seeking behavior. All of which were encompassing the development and humanitarian contexts. UNICEF directly supported 41,064 conflict-affected children (19,255 girls and 21,809 boys) across Rakhine, Kachin and Shan state. UNICEF also conducted conflict sensitivity analysis for Child Protection programming in Rakhine to ensure planned activities are relevant and do-no-harm. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:28/07/2020
